# Step 1: Generate RSA private key for Alice
openssl genpkey -algorithm RSA -out alice.key

# Step 2: Extract Alice’s public key
openssl pkey -pubout -in alice.key -out alice.pub

# Step 3: View private key details
openssl pkey -in alice.key -text -noout

# Step 4: View public key details
openssl pkey -pubin -in alice.pub -text -noout

# Step 5: Create a Certificate Signing Request (CSR) for Alice
openssl req -new -key alice.key -out alice.csr

# Step 6: Generate RSA private key for Root CA
openssl genpkey -algorithm RSA -out root.key

# Step 7: Create a CSR for Root CA
openssl req -new -key root.key -out root.csr

# Step 8: View Alice’s CSR
cat alice.csr

# Step 9: View Root CA’s CSR
cat root.csr

===========================================
✅ This file covers the CSR workflow:

    Key generation (Alice + Root CA)

    Public key extraction

    CSR creation for both Alice and Root CA

    Viewing CSR contents

👉 Next natural step is to sign Alice’s CSR with the Root CA key to produce a certificate (alice.crt). That will complete the PKI chain of trust simulation.


===================================
📄 Signing CSR with Root CA Commands (Topic 14)

# Step 1: Generate RSA private key for Root CA (already done)
openssl genpkey -algorithm RSA -out root.key

# Step 2: Create a self-signed Root CA certificate (valid 365 days)
openssl req -x509 -new -key root.key -out root.crt -days 365

# Step 3: Sign Alice’s CSR with Root CA
openssl x509 -req -in alice.csr -CA root.crt -CAkey root.key -CAcreateserial -out alice.crt -days 365

# Step 4: View Alice’s signed certificate
openssl x509 -in alice.crt -text -noout

# Step 5: Verify Alice’s certificate against Root CA
openssl verify -CAfile root.crt alice.crt

===========================================

✅ This completes the PKI chain of trust simulation:

    Root CA issues its own certificate

    Alice’s CSR is signed by Root CA

    Alice now has a valid certificate trusted by the Root CA
